I made this with the Dark Chocolate Souffles to bring to a friend's house. This custard really made the dish, and the others agreed. We all had second servings of custard over our souffles as we worked our way through them. Lovely.

Rating: 4
This was a fantastic recipe. Very easy and very elegant. I will certainly be making this again.

Rating: 3
I was eager to try this recipe, having just had the most divine cardamom creme anglaise at a local restuarant. I would recommend reducing the sugar. While the fragrance of the creme was exquisite, my family (including two children age 7 and 11) found it much too sweet.

Rating: 4
This is so yummy, especially with the chocolate souffles. However, if you are making it a day in advance (as I did), be sure to strain out the cardamom pods after a few hours like the recipe says. I forgot to take them out until the next day and I ended up having to make it again because the cardamom flavor had become overpowering. Done correctly, though, this is delicious.

Rating: 4
I never did look up the choc. souffle recipe this apparently was first written with, but it doesn't matter. This is a perfect sauce for any spice cake, even to dress up a favourite carrot cake instead of icing. Also, if you double or triple the recipe and don't thicken it on the stove, you can use it as the custard base for a great creme brule!

Rating: 4
Absolutely wonderful. I used Valrhona chocolate and the souffles were great. The Creme Anglaise had a uniqueness to them from the Cardamom that complimented the sweetness of the souffles perfectly. Can't wait to make these again.

Rating: 4
